Welcome back to The Best & The Brightest. I=E2=80=99m Leigh Ann
Caldwell, with you on another Sunday ahead of a busy week in Washington.=C2=
=A0

=C2=A0

Yes, anger toward Elon Musk has erupted everywhere, and is reaching far bey=
ond the liberal ecosystem. Two weeks ago, for instance, a nonpolitical frie=
nd asked me to explain DOGE. This week, she said her book club session had =
been dedicated to Musk=E2=80=99s chainsaw-wielding CPAC appearance
and Rep. Greg Casar=E2=80=99s viral clip in which he highlighted the $8 mil=
lion per day that Musk=E2=80=99s companies receive in government contracts.=
 But the new injection of energy in the Democratic Party does not mean ever=
ything is okay, or in any way suggest that a leaderless party has been unit=
ed.

=C2=A0

In today=E2=80=99s issue, the latest reporting and intrigue on those fault =
lines. A week after my
conversation with Rep. Adam Smith, I received a lot of outreach from member=
s further to the left in the party who rejected any blame for the Trump lan=
dslide and current malaise. I also spoke with Bernie Sanders, Pramila Jayap=
al, and many others about their plans for what the party needs to become. F=
aiz Shakir, who ran Sanders=E2=80=99 2020 presidential campaign and briefly=
 ran for Democratic National
Committee chair, said that early signals from the party suggest that many D=
emocrats are finally embracing Sanders=E2=80=99 message of economic equalit=
y. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s easy to be in opposition to Trump and Musk, becaus=
e it codes as partisan,=E2=80=9D Shakir told me. But are Democratic lawmake=
rs willing to go after their own billionaires, too? More on that below the =
fold.

=C2=A0

But first=E2=80=A6=C2=A0

* Making
his-story: Trump=E2=80=99s insistence on forging his own version of reality=
, this time blaming Ukraine for initiating a war that Russia clearly starte=
d, is familiar in part because the playbook has been so successful. In the =
months after the 2020 election, for example, 55 percent of Republicans beli=
eved ( https://www.ipsos.com/en-us/news-polls/majority-republicans-still-be=
lieve-2020-election-was-stolen-donald-trump?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The=
+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+B=
rightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) Trump had won
the election. By the fall of 2022, that number had climbed to 63 percent; i=
n the summer of 2023, it was 69 percent, according ( https://www.cnn.com/20=
23/08/03/politics/cnn-poll-republicans-think-2020-election-illegitimate/ind=
ex.html?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2=
F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F2=
5%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617=
da42abd12a ) to CNN polling. Meanwhile, Trump has unrelentingly shifted pub=
lic opinion on the January 6 riot at the Capitol, by continuously and false=
ly insisting that they were peaceful protestors, despite all
video evidence to the contrary. (A recent Washington Post/Ipsos poll ( http=
s://www.washingtonpost.com/tablet/2025/02/19/feb-13-18-2025-washington-post=
-ipsos-poll/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2=
F23%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F2=
3%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c=
60617da42abd12a ) found that 83 percent of Americans oppose Trump=E2=80=99s=
 pardons of people who were charged with violent crimes committed on that d=
ay, but don=E2=80=99t be surprised if that number decreases with time.)

There hasn=E2=80=99t been a lot of polling on the percentage of Americans w=
ho
think Ukraine started the war, presumably because it wasn=E2=80=99t a quest=
ion that needed to be asked until Trump invented it. A YouGov online survey=
 conducted this week found ( https://today.yougov.com/topics/politics/surve=
y-results/daily/2025/02/20/05ee7/4?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightes=
t+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+=
-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcust=
omer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) that just 6 percent of Americans th=
ink Ukraine started the war. I=E2=80=99m going to watch to see if these num=
bers tick up, should Trump double down on this spurious
counterfactual.

Americans remain overwhelmingly in favor of Ukraine over Russia, according =
to data shared with Puck by Echelon insights, but those numbers have soften=
ed over time as Trump and other members of the far right have shifted their=
 rhetoric. Two years ago, about eight in 10 Americans said they sided more =
with Ukraine. Today, that number is below 60 percent. Among Republicans, it=
 is closer to 50 percent.

North Carolina Republican Senator Thom Tillis,
despite giving a feisty speech in defense of Ukraine on the Senate floor Th=
ursday, dismissed Trump=E2=80=99s Putin-friendly position as =E2=80=9Cgrowi=
ng pains=E2=80=9D in the early stages of a new presidency, when =E2=80=9Ca =
lot of weird things happen.=E2=80=9D He said that if the rhetoric and actio=
ns toward Russia are the same come April, he=E2=80=99ll be concerned. We=E2=
=80=99ll see=E2=80=A6
* Mike Johnson in the hot seat: It=E2=80=99s another big week for Speaker M=
ike Johnson. A vote is
expected Tuesday on Republicans=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Cone big beautiful=E2=80=
=9D budget framework, which calls for $4.5 trillion to extend Trump=E2=80=
=99s tax cuts, and at least $1.5 trillion in budget cuts=E2=80=94moves whic=
h will likely touch Medicaid and other government benefits like SNAP. It=E2=
=80=99s still unclear whether Johnson can rally his razor-thin majority beh=
ind the bill.

The framework, which lacks policy details, could become a political liabili=
ty for Johnson=E2=80=99s party. Democratic campaign officials are already p=
reparing
attacks on members in swing districts for voting to extend tax breaks which=
 disproportionately help the wealthy while slashing government services.=C2=
=A0

Vulnerable members are very aware of these dynamics, and Johnson has been w=
orking overtime to calm them, by reinforcing that this is just a first step=
 to help move the process forward. He=E2=80=99s telling them that they=E2=
=80=99ll have a hand in helping to shape the policy=E2=80=94i.e., the corre=
ct balance of budget cuts and tax cuts, with an end
result they can justify to constituents. If he=E2=80=99s able to move this =
forward on Tuesday, it=E2=80=99ll be another win for Johnson, but the vote =
whipping will only get harder from here.

Now for the main event=E2=80=A6

Scenes From the Democratic Marriage ( https://puck.news/elon-musk-is-showin=
g-himself-to-be-a-soft-target-for-democrats/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+Th=
e+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+=
