A month after the inauguration, rival Democratic factions are coalescing ar=
ound the
potency of an anti-billionaire messaging. On the topic of pretty much every=
thing else, however, they are aligned in agreeing to disagree.

Leigh Ann Caldwell ( https://puck.news/author/leigh-ann-caldwell/?utm_campa=
ign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_conten=
t=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_medium=
=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Leigh Ann Caldwell ( https://puck.news/author/leigh-ann-caldwell/?utm_campa=
ign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_conten=
t=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_medium=
=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Much has changed in the week since Rep. Adam Smith, the vocal
Washington State Democrat, professed to me that his party had moved too far=
 left on issues of culture and inclusion. Smith, as you=E2=80=99ll recall, =
said ( https://puck.news/rep-adam-smiths-advice-to-democrats/?utm_campaign=
=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_content=
=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_medium=3D=
email_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) that =
the Democrats had forgotten about personal accountability, and he called ou=
t the party for =E2=80=9Cframing everything as, It=E2=80=99s a human right=
=E2=80=94you know, healthcare, transportation, asylum, all of that=E2=80=94=
implying there=E2=80=99s no
responsibility on the other side. I think that message cost us some support=
=2E=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

In recent days, however, previously bewildered Democrats have slowly been e=
merging from their post-election daze with a renewed sense of purpose, and =
maybe even rallying around a unified message. It=E2=80=99s a shift for thos=
e in the party who have spent the last three months finger-pointing and sca=
pegoating each other for losing to a
convicted felon. Furious and fearful voters have been channeling their rage=
 through the Capitol switchboard, jamming phone lines, desperate to get the=
 ear of their representatives to vent about being fired from their governme=
nt job, or the slashing of federal agencies, or the prospect of losing fede=
ral benefits. Several members felt the heat in person during a week back ho=
me in their districts, where town hall venues struggled to contain the mass=
es of constituents or their anger. To
wit: Democratic Rep. Brad Schneider=E2=80=99s telephone town hall had 11,00=
0 participants. Rep. Rich McCormick, a Republican from Georgia, was capture=
d on video getting booed ( https://edition.cnn.com/2025/02/21/politics/vide=
o/rich-mccormick-town-hall-trump-power-digvid?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+T=
he+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The=
+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F23%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_so=
urce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ). The list of lawmakers b=
eing confronted by voters is long.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I=E2=80=99ve been told by lawmakers, aides, and fundraisers that the grassr=
oots fury from activists and donors, alike, has finally started to break th=
rough to Democrats on the Hill. Members, however, are still trying to keep =
their voters=E2=80=99 expectations at bay until government funding runs out=
 in a few weeks=E2=80=94their first real legislative chance to force Trump=
=E2=80=99s and Republicans=E2=80=99 hands. Interestingly, however, the pres=
sure still hasn=E2=80=99t led to unity, and mistrust between the ideologica=
l
wings continues to simmer. Emblematic of the divide are two Washington Stat=
e lawmakers who represent different parts of Seattle. Soon after I spoke wi=
th Smith, I heard from Rep. Pramila Jayapal, who took issue with the =E2=80=
=9CRepublican-light=E2=80=9D perception of her party.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Jayapal told me she adamantly disagrees with Smith=E2=80=99s theory about t=
he roots of Democrats=E2=80=99 losses. =E2=80=9CWe lost people because we d=
id not, as a
party, focus on lifting up working people, on really speaking to people who=
 felt like we weren=E2=80=99t fighting for them,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=
=9CAnd a lot of that, frankly, came from centrist Democrats over the decade=
s.=E2=80=9D Jayapal pointed to moderate Democrats blocking Biden-era legisl=
ation such as housing assistance, which she says would have appealed to the=
 Democratic voters who either stayed home or voted for Trump. =E2=80=9CThis=
 is a difficult moment for us,=E2=80=9D she told me, underscoring the
obvious.=C2=A0

One
Thing to Agree On
-----------------

Yet there are indications that, for the first time in years, Democrats may =
at least be
pulling together around a clear and concise economic message of the billion=
aires versus everyone else=E2=80=94the Bernie Sanders approach that has bee=
n shunned, and sometimes mocked, by the broader party in the past. That lin=
e of attack never gained much traction during the 2020 race, in part becaus=
e Trump=E2=80=99s focus on cultural issues kept his opponents off-balance. =
But Elon Musk, the world=E2=80=99s richest man, firing tens of thousands of=
 civil servants is a layup for
Democrats. The left couldn=E2=80=99t have dreamt up a better bogeyman than =
a billionaire laying off veterans while wielding a gold chainsaw at CPAC.

=C2=A0

Sanders, the Vermont Independent who despises the Clinton wing of the party=
, has been preaching the same economic populist message since he ran for ma=
yor of Burlington in 1981. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s no great secret that for t=
he last many decades, Democrats have lost
the support of working-class people,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9COne of t=
he reasons is that, in fact, the party has been increasingly captured by bi=
g money, by consultants and by policies that have not benefited ordinary pe=
ople.=E2=80=9D But, Sanders continued, Trump=E2=80=99s unabashed embrace of=
 oligarchs=E2=80=94and, frankly, the oligarchy=E2=80=99s reciprocal wet kis=
s=E2=80=94has provided an opportunity for Democrats to reengage their core =
constituency.

=C2=A0

When
I spoke with Rep. Greg Casar, the new head of the Progressive Caucus, he ag=
reed that Musk=E2=80=99s ascension had created =E2=80=9Ca real opportunity=
=E2=80=9D for Democrats to win back the =E2=80=9Cbroad swath of working-cla=
ss voters=E2=80=9D that was once central to the Democratic coalition but ha=
s been inexorably moving away from the party. According to Faiz Shakir, who=
 operated Sanders=E2=80=99 2020 presidential campaign and briefly ran for D=
emocratic National Committee chair, early signals do suggest
Democrats are embracing Sanders=E2=80=99 message of economic justice for th=
e working class. Still, he warned that it=E2=80=99s way too early to determ=
ine whether Democrats can be trusted as the pro-worker party. There=E2=80=
=99s a lot of culture war baggage that needs to be tucked away.

=C2=A0

One Democratic strategist, who is still in the throes of conducting a revie=
w of the last election, said that the billionaires=E2=80=93versus=E2=80=93m=
iddle-class messaging is
directionally right. I=E2=80=99m told, however, that Democrats still aren=
=E2=80=99t convening meetings between intraparty rivals, to talk and strate=
gize, nor are those much-needed conversations happening in the weekly House=
 Democratic Caucus meetings. Instead, the issues are broached in group text=
s, where a lot is left unsaid. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s easy to be in oppositi=
on to Trump and Musk, because it codes as partisan,=E2=80=9D Shakir told me=
=2E =E2=80=9CThe real integrity is if y=
ou=E2=80=99re willing to take on the w=
ealthy class, even if some of
them might be supportive of you.=E2=80=9D

