<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">Yet there are indications that, for the first time in years, Democrats =
may at least be
pulling together around a clear and concise economic message of <em>the bil=
lionaires versus everyone else</em>=E2=80=94the <strong>Bernie Sanders</str=
ong> approach that has been shunned, and sometimes mocked, by the broader p=
arty in the past. That line of attack never gained much traction during the=
 2020 race, in part because Trump=E2=80=99s focus on cultural issues kept h=
is opponents off-balance. But <strong>Elon Musk</strong>, the world=E2=80=
=99s richest man, firing tens of thousands of civil servants is a layup for
Democrats. The left couldn=E2=80=99t have dreamt up a better bogeyman than =
a billionaire laying off veterans while wielding a gold chainsaw at CPAC.</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;m=
argin-bottom:0px;">Sanders, the Vermont Independent who despises the <stron=
g>Clinton </strong>wing of the party, has been preaching the same economic =
populist message since he ran for mayor of Burlington in 1981. =E2=80=9CIt=
=E2=80=99s no great secret that for the last many decades, Democrats have l=
ost
the support of working-class people,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9COne of t=
he reasons is that, in fact, the party has been increasingly captured by bi=
g money, by consultants and by policies that have not benefited ordinary pe=
ople.=E2=80=9D But, Sanders continued, Trump=E2=80=99s unabashed embrace of=
 oligarchs=E2=80=94and, frankly, the oligarchy=E2=80=99s reciprocal wet kis=
s=E2=80=94has provided an opportunity for Democrats to reengage their core =
constituency.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">When
I spoke with Rep. <strong>Greg Casar</strong>, the new head of the Progress=
ive Caucus, he agreed that Musk=E2=80=99s ascension had created =E2=80=9Ca =
real opportunity=E2=80=9D for Democrats to win back the =E2=80=9Cbroad swat=
h of working-class voters=E2=80=9D that was once central to the Democratic =
coalition but has been inexorably moving away from the party. According to =
<strong>Faiz Shakir</strong>, who operated Sanders=E2=80=99 2020 presidenti=
al campaign and briefly ran for Democratic National Committee chair, early =
signals do suggest
Democrats are embracing Sanders=E2=80=99 message of economic justice for th=
e working class. Still, he warned that it=E2=80=99s way too early to determ=
ine whether Democrats can be trusted as the pro-worker party. There=E2=80=
=99s a lot of culture war baggage that needs to be tucked away.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">One Democ=
ratic strategist, who is still in the throes of conducting a review of the =
last election, said that the billionaires=E2=80=93versus=E2=80=93middle-cla=
ss messaging is
directionally right. I=E2=80=99m told, however, that Democrats still aren=
=E2=80=99t convening meetings between intraparty rivals, to talk and strate=
gize, nor are those much-needed conversations happening in the weekly House=
 Democratic Caucus meetings. Instead, the issues are broached in group text=
s, where a lot is left unsaid. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s easy to be in oppositi=
on to Trump and Musk, because it codes as partisan,=E2=80=9D Shakir told me=
=2E =E2=80=9CThe real integrity is if y=
ou=E2=80=99re willing to take on the w=
ealthy class, even if some of
them might be supportive of you.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
